          "id": "medquad-chunk-0c2d6489fe309363",
          "title": "What is (are) Acid Lipase Disease ?",
          "content": "Acid lipase disease, also referred to as acid lipase deficiency, is a medical condition that arises when the body does not produce enough of a crucial enzyme needed to break down certain types of fats. These fats, known as lipids, encompass a variety of substances, including fatty acids, oils, and cholesterol. When this enzyme is absent or insufficient, these lipids can build up in the cells and tissues of the body, leading to significant health complications.\nThere are two particularly rare disorders that stem from this deficiency: Wolman's disease and cholesteryl ester storage disease.\nWolman's disease is classified as an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that a child must inherit the defective gene from both parents to develop the condition. This disorder is marked by an accumulation of cholesteryl esters and triglycerides, which are forms of fat that the body normally processes. Infants born with Wolman's disease may initially seem healthy, but they can quickly develop serious health issues. Some of the symptoms include developmental delays, low muscle tone, an enlarged liver and spleen, and various gastrointestinal problems. These infants may also experience jaundice, which is a yellowing of the skin and eyes, anemia, vomiting, and the formation of calcium deposits in the adrenal glands, leading to hardening of these glands. Both boys and girls can be affected by this condition, and early diagnosis is crucial for managing symptoms effectively.\nCholesteryl ester storage disease (CESD) is another rare disorder associated with acid lipase deficiency. This condition results in the storage of cholesteryl esters and triglycerides in the blood, lymphatic system, and lymphoid tissues. Children with CESD often develop an enlarged liver, which can progress to cirrhosis and chronic liver failure if not addressed. Similar to Wolman's disease, children with CESD may also experience calcium deposits in the adrenal glands and jaundice. The onset of symptoms can vary widely among individuals, and in some cases, the disorder may not be diagnosed until adulthood.\nUnderstanding these conditions is important for recognizing the signs and symptoms early, which can lead to better management and treatment options. Research into acid lipase deficiency continues to evolve, providing hope for improved therapies and outcomes for those affected by these rare diseases.\nContext recap: Acid lipase disease, also referred to as acid lipase deficiency, is a medical condition that arises when the body does not produce enough of a crucial enzyme needed to break down certain types of fats. These fats, known as lipids, encompass a variety of substances, including fatty acids, oils, and cholesterol. When this enzyme is absent or insufficient, these lipids can build up in the cells and tissues of the body, leading to significant health complications. There are two particularly rare disorders that stem from this deficiency: Wolman's disease and cholesteryl ester storage disease.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Acid Lipase Disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Neurology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Acid lipase disease, also referred to as acid lipase deficiency, is a medical condition that arises when the body does not produce enough of a crucial enzyme needed to break down certain types of fats. These fats, known as lipids, encompass a variety of substances, including fatty acids, oils, and cholesterol. When this enzyme is absent or insufficient, these lipids can build up in the cells and tissues of the body, leading to significant health complications. There are two particularly rare disorders that stem from this deficiency: Wolman's disease and cholesteryl ester storage disease.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Acid Lipase Disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Neurology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
