          "title": "What is the outlook for Canavan Disease ?",
          "content": "Canavan Disease is a rare and serious genetic condition that affects the brain. The outlook for children diagnosed with Canavan Disease can be quite difficult. Sadly, many children with this condition do not live beyond the age of 10. However, there are some cases where individuals may survive into their teenage years or even their early twenties. This situation underscores the critical need for continued research into Canavan Disease and the importance of providing support and resources for families who are affected by this condition. By understanding the challenges faced by those with Canavan Disease, we can work towards better treatments and a brighter future for these children.\nContext recap: Canavan Disease is a rare and serious genetic condition that affects the brain. The outlook for children diagnosed with Canavan Disease can be quite difficult. Sadly, many children with this condition do not live beyond the age of 10. However, there are some cases where individuals may survive into their teenage years or even their early twenties.\nWhy this matters: What is the outlook for Canavan Disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Neurology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Canavan Disease is a rare and serious genetic condition that affects the brain. The outlook for children diagnosed with Canavan Disease can be quite difficult. Sadly, many children with this condition do not live beyond the age of 10. However, there are some cases where individuals may survive into their teenage years or even their early twenties.\nWhy this matters: What is the outlook for Canavan Disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Neurology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Canavan Disease is a rare and serious genetic condition that affects the brain. The outlook for children diagnosed with Canavan Disease can be quite difficult. Sadly, many children with this condition do not live beyond the age of 10. However, there are some cases where individuals may survive into their teenage years or even their early twenties.\nWhy this matters: What is the outlook for Canavan Disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Neurology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
