          "id": "medquad-chunk-6618ccfe2d20033b",
          "title": "What is the outlook for Craniosynostosis ?",
          "content": "Craniosynostosis is a condition that affects the shape of a baby's head due to the early closure of one or more of the cranial sutures, which are the fibrous joints between the bones of the skull. The outlook for children with craniosynostosis can vary quite a bit. If only one suture is involved and there are no other health issues, the prognosis is generally positive. These children often have successful outcomes after treatment. However, if multiple sutures are involved or if there are additional abnormalities, the outlook may be more complex. Each case is unique, and healthcare providers will assess the specific situation to determine the best course of action.\nContext recap: Craniosynostosis is a condition that affects the shape of a baby's head due to the early closure of one or more of the cranial sutures, which are the fibrous joints between the bones of the skull. The outlook for children with craniosynostosis can vary quite a bit. If only one suture is involved and there are no other health issues, the prognosis is generally positive. These children often have successful outcomes after treatment.\nWhy this matters: What is the outlook for Craniosynostosis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Neurology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Craniosynostosis is a condition that affects the shape of a baby's head due to the early closure of one or more of the cranial sutures, which are the fibrous joints between the bones of the skull. The outlook for children with craniosynostosis can vary quite a bit. If only one suture is involved and there are no other health issues, the prognosis is generally positive. These children often have successful outcomes after treatment.\nWhy this matters: What is the outlook for Craniosynostosis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Neurology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Craniosynostosis is a condition that affects the shape of a baby's head due to the early closure of one or more of the cranial sutures, which are the fibrous joints between the bones of the skull. The outlook for children with craniosynostosis can vary quite a bit. If only one suture is involved and there are no other health issues, the prognosis is generally positive. These children often have successful outcomes after treatment.\nWhy this matters: What is the outlook for Craniosynostosis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Neurology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
