      "flashcards": [
        {
          "id": "meadow-1b9f660383fcab01",
          "front": "How many neurons are involved in the lateral corticospinal tract pathway, which is responsible for voluntary muscle movement?",
          "back": "The lateral corticospinal tract pathway, which is responsible for voluntary muscle movement, involves two neurons: the upper motor neuron (UMN) and the lower motor neuron (LMN). The UMN originates in the primary motor cortex in the brain and travels down through the internal capsule, the brainstem, and the spinal cord. The UMN synapses with the LMN in the anterior horn of the spinal cord. The LMN then carries the motor information from the spinal cord to the muscles, causing them to contract. Damage to either the UMN or LMN can result in motor deficits, such as weakness or paralysis. Understanding the organization and function of neural pathways such as the lateral corticospinal tract is important in the study of neuroscience and neurology."
        },
        {
          "id": "meadow-b5bad7f37252e6a3",
          "front": "How many neurons are involved in the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway?",
          "back": "The dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway, which is responsible for transmitting fine touch, vibration, and proprioceptive information from the body to the brain, involves three neurons. The first neuron is located in the dorsal root ganglion and carries the sensory information from the receptor to the spinal cord. The second neuron is located in the dorsal column nuclei of the medulla oblongata and carries the information across the midline of the brainstem. The third neuron is located in the thalamus and carries the information to the primary somatosensory cortex in the brain. The organization and function of neural pathways such as the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway are important in the study of neuroscience and neurology."
        }
      ]
