          "id": "medquad-chunk-c807524e68fd3950",
          "title": "What is (are) Holoprosencephaly ?",
          "content": "Holoprosencephaly is a medical condition that occurs when the brain does not divide properly into two halves during early development in the womb. This failure to separate can lead to the formation of a brain that has only one lobe instead of the usual two lobes. Additionally, this condition can result in significant issues with the shape and structure of the skull and facial features. In many cases, the malformations associated with holoprosencephaly are so severe that babies may not survive until birth. However, there are instances where some babies are born with nearly normal brain function, although they may have noticeable facial differences that can affect their eyes, nose, and upper lip.\nHoloprosencephaly is classified into three main types, each with varying degrees of severity. The first type is called Alobar holoprosencephaly, where the brain has not divided at all. This type is often associated with serious facial deformities, making it the most severe form of the condition. The second type, known as Semilobar holoprosencephaly, occurs when there is some division of the brain, leading to moderate symptoms and facial differences. Lastly, Lobar holoprosencephaly shows more separation of the brain hemispheres and is considered the least severe form of the disorder. In some cases of lobar holoprosencephaly, the brain may appear almost normal, which can lead to better outcomes for the affected individuals.\nThe facial anomalies associated with holoprosencephaly can vary widely in severity. The mildest form of facial difference is a median cleft lip, which is a small split in the upper lip. On the other hand, the most severe facial anomaly is known as cyclopia. In cyclopia, a single eye is present in the area where the nose typically is, and this condition may also involve a missing nose or a tubular-shaped nose located above the eye. Other notable facial anomalies include ethmocephaly, where a proboscis, or tubular structure, is found between closely-set eyes, and cebocephaly, which is characterized by a small, flat nose with a single nostril located below underdeveloped eyes. Understanding these variations is important for medical professionals and families affected by this condition, as it can help in planning for care and support for those impacted by holoprosencephaly.\nContext recap: Holoprosencephaly is a medical condition that occurs when the brain does not divide properly into two halves during early development in the womb. This failure to separate can lead to the formation of a brain that has only one lobe instead of the usual two lobes. Additionally, this condition can result in significant issues with the shape and structure of the skull and facial features. In many cases, the malformations associated with holoprosencephaly are so severe that babies may not survive until birth.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Holoprosencephaly ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Neurology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Holoprosencephaly is a medical condition that occurs when the brain does not divide properly into two halves during early development in the womb. This failure to separate can lead to the formation of a brain that has only one lobe instead of the usual two lobes. Additionally, this condition can result in significant issues with the shape and structure of the skull and facial features. In many cases, the malformations associated with holoprosencephaly are so severe that babies may not survive until birth.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Holoprosencephaly ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Neurology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
